\section{Troubadour}
\label{troubadour}
d3 4
a6 15
In a DragonQuest world, a minstrel who wishes to be welcome for their
entertainment abilities during their travels is known as a troubadour.

A troubadour becomes a multi-talented performer as they increase their
experience in the field. The troubadour is also a student of the
people they visit, and is as knowledgeable as a scholar in the matter
of customs.  A troubadour, being a skilled actor, can also be a master
of disguise.  The most useful ability a troubadour will gain is their
bardic voice, which enables them to influence the actions of all but
the deaf.

The abilities subsumed in the troubadour rules are usable by such a
character in situations not explicitly covered in the next few pages.
The GM should improvise and allow a troubadour character to use their
skill in appropriate instances.
d10 143
a152 93
\subsubsection{A troubadour acquires one ability per Rank.}

The character begins with one of the following abilities at Rank 0.
All acquired abilities can be performed skillfully.

\begin{enumerate}
\renewcommand{\itemsep}{0pt}
\item Play the instrument of the player's choice. The troubadour must
acquire this ability anew for each separate instrument they wish to
use.
\item	Sing or chant.
\item	Recite stories and legends.
\item	Compose stories and legends.
\item	Perform mime.
\item	Mimic speech.
\item	Act out skits or parody.
\item	Tell and compose jokes.
\item	Dance (especially folk dance).
\item	Dress appropriately to all situations.
\item	Simulate wide range of emotions.
\item	Execute acrobatics.
\item	Amuse small children.
\item	Amuse  semi-intelligent   creatures.
\item	Appear attractive.
\end{enumerate}

A troubadour may gain additional abilities after achieving Rank 10
by the expenditure of 500 Experience Points per ability.

\subsubsection{A troubadour's chance of successfully performing minor
magic is increased by 2\% per Rank.}

\subsubsection{When a troubadour uses their Perception value to gain
information about the customs or habits of humanoids, add 2 per Rank
they have achieved to their success percentage.}

\subsubsection{A troubadour can use disguise to appear of a different
humanoid race, gender, or profession.}

A troubadour cannot disguise themself as a member of a race for which
their size is inappropriate (e.g., an elf troubadour cannot disguise
themself as a halfling) or as practitioner of a profession for which
they are physically unsuited (e.g., a frost giant troubadour could not
imitate a jockey).  A troubadour's disguise ability is intended to
fool someone who does not know the humanoid the troubadour is
masquerading; if the troubadour is attempting to pass themself off as
an acquaintance of a particular being, the GM will have to determine
the chance of the substitution being noticed.

A troubadour's base success percentage to use their disguise ability is
(12 \x Rank)\%.  Subtract:

\begin{enumerate}
\item
Two times the Perception of the being to be deceived by the troubadour
if the troubadour is impersonating a member of their own race.

\item
Four times the Perception of the being to be deceived by the
troubadour if the troubadour is impersonating a member of another
race.

\item
(11 - Troubadour's Rank) if they impersonate a person of opposite
gender.
\end{enumerate}

If the GM's roll on percentile dice is equal to or less than the
troubadour's success percentage, the being to whom the troubadour is
falsely representing themself is taken in.  If the roll is greater
than the success percentage, the being notices inconsistencies (with
the role being assumed) in the troubadour's appearance or behaviour.
The inconsistency becomes more glaring as the roll approaches 100.  If
a troubadour is using disguise in close proximity to a being, a check
against their success percentage must be made every hour.

\subsubsection{A troubadour can use their bardic voice to charm several
beings at once.}

A troubadour may use their bardic voice on not more than (2 + 2 \x
Rank) beings who can understand the language which they speak.  The
troubadour may not use the voice ability in combat, but may use it
against hostile beings.  A Willpower check must be made for every
being the troubadour hopes to affect.  The success percentage for the
Willpower check is (10 \x Troubadour's Rank - 2 \x Being's
Willpower)\%.  If the roll is less than or equal to the success
percentage, the being is charmed, as described in the College of
Ensorcelments and Enchantments spell of the same name (see
\S\ref{e-and-e}).  If the roll is greater than the success percentage,
the being is not affected.

A troubadour must expend (15 - Rank) Fatigue Points every time they
use the bardic voice ability.
@


